The second molar (#17) is positioned higher in the alveolar ridge than the adjacent teeth, giving it a more eruptive appearance; the crown is more coronally exposed, and the cervical enamel appears slightly more. At the cervical region of #17 there is a visible band of plaque accumulation, appearing as a thin, yellowish‑gray layer adhering to the enamel margin. The gingival tissue surrounding #17 shows a yellow‑brown pigment deposition, giving the marginal gingiva a subtle discoloration that contrasts with the pink, healthy gingiva seen elsewhere. No ulcerations, swelling, or bleeding are noted in the surrounding soft tissue. 

The overall soft‑tissue architecture appears normal, with a well‑contoured attached gingiva and a healthy depth of the buccal vestibule. A cheek retractor is visible, gently pulling the cheek away to expose the labial surfaces, and a small intra‑oral mirror can be seen reflecting the posterior aspect of the teeth, aiding the visualization of the cervical areas. No dental restorations, car, or prosthetic appliances are evident in the captured region. The lighting is even, highlighting the natural translucency of the enamel and the color variations of the gingiva, allowing clear identification of the plaque and pigment changes noted on tooth #17."}

